Review: Huh. Note: the Tubi version is clearly a recorded VHS rip, tracking notices and all.
You can tell this is a modern day fairy tale because all the cops are decent people and Rosie Perez can simultaneously get and heal from a boob job in what's implied to be a few days to a week.
It's a very boilerplate period sports movie without much drive to it. Extremely grandparentcore.

If it weren't for Nicolas Cage having a ball as the Lord of Evil and Father of Vampires and some fun decay makeup in the opening, there'd be little to no reason to watch this. There's too much gore for the YA crowd, the gore is obvious CG blood that is distracting and disappears once the shot angle changes. The comedy was groanworthy, except for a bit where a fellow support group member gets pissed at Renfield's constant interrupting of her personal sharing.
You know those films you warn people not to watch when they're depressed and suicidal? Yeah, this is the exact opposite of that. Go watch in theaters while you can.

Michael Rooker is giving his best as a badass demon hunting priest, Tony Todd gets to play an isolationist kook, and a woman is briefly topless. That's about as positive as I can get with this film. Makes sense why it was DTV.
You took a perfectly good tulpa and gave it depression?

What kind of horror movie keeps Evil Dead levels of gore and porn levels of acting while using post production to remove all audio of curse words from the dialogue? This kind evidently, a movie all about a slow moving man with a rubber mallet and a cameraman's fixation on filming actresses thongs poking out of their tight jeans.

The weakest of the Barker adaptations I've seen (yes, even worse than Rawhead Rex). The lead characters are consistently inconsistent and the final twist is incredibly misguided and didn't really work. Only pluses are a particularly nasty opening effect work for the gorehounds, and a substantial amount of both male and female nudity for the horndogs.

Review: Brendan Gleeson and Oliver Platt had more chemistry than Fonda and Pullman... oh, there is a giant croc in here too.
More Milana Vayntrub in movies, please. Funny and easy on the eyes.Characters were written fairly bland but performances of the two leads helps carry the film as Clue-lite.
